<p class="lead"><strong>Spreadsheets programs offer users options for both controlling how a user views the document on the computer screen as well as controlling how the spreadsheet document prints.</strong></p class="lead">


<p>What you see on the screen and what gets printed may be two different things, depending on how you have the options setup.</p>

<p><strong>Viewing Options</strong> offer the user choices for how the spreadsheet will be shown as it is viewed on the computer screen. The reason for these different viewing options is to empower users to customize what they want to see on the screen so they can work with the data they need more easily.</p>

<p>With Viewing Options, users can zoom in or magnify data in the spreadsheet, hide (and then unhide) rows and/or columns, freeze (and unfreeze) panes and more. One of the most helpful View Options is to freeze and unfreeze panes in a worksheet.</p>

<h4>Freeze and Unfreeze Panes</h4>

<p>As you scroll through a worksheet, especially larger worksheets with many columns and rows of data, the column and row headings may no longer be able to be seen. In order to keep the data in the column or row headings visible, spreadsheet programs allow you to <strong>freeze (hold in place)</strong> selected rows and/or columns.</p> 

<p>In the example below, the <strong>row and column labels</strong> that help you make sense of the numbers are highlighted.</p> 


<img class="img-wrap style1" src="images/spreadsheets/freezepaneex1.jpg" alt="">
<br />
<br />

<p>If you scroll to the right, the <strong>row labels</strong> in column A disappear and you cannot tell which grades go with which person. </p> 



<img class="img-wrap style1" src="images/spreadsheets/freezepaneex2.jpg" alt="">
<br />
<br />


 
<p>The frozen columns and rows are called <strong> panes</strong>. To freeze the row labels, you must place your cursor in a cell and select freeze panes. The spreadsheet will freeze the cells <strong>to the left and above</strong> the cell you choose.</p> 


<p>Using this tool, you can scroll through the spreadsheet data, but the panes or portions of the worksheet that are frozen will not move.</p>


<p>How you access the tool to Freeze Panes depends on your version.</p>


